{{redirect|Di Nunno|the basketball player|Mike DiNunno}}
'''Giulia Di Nunno''' (born 1973){{r|iciam}} is an Italian mathematician specializing in [[Stochastic calculus|stochastic analysis]] and [[financial mathematics]] who works as a professor of mathematics at the [[University of Oslo]], with an adjunct appointment at the [[Norwegian School of Economics]].{{r|cv}}
As well as for her research, Di Nunno is known for promoting mathematics in Africa.{{r|iciam}}

==Education and career==
Di Nunno earned a degree in mathematics from the [[University of Milan]] in 1998, including research on stochastic functions with Yurii Rozanov.{{r|cv}} She moved to the [[University of Pavia]] for doctoral studies, continuing with Rozanov as an informal mentor but under the official supervision of Eugenio Regazzini. She completed her Ph.D. in 2003; her dissertation was ''On stochastic differentiation with applications to minimal variance hedging''.{{r|cv|mgp}}
She joined the University of Oslo in 2003, and added her affiliation with the Norwegian School of Economics in 2009.{{r|cv}}

==Activism==
Di Nunno is the chair of the [[European Mathematical Society]]'s Committee for Developing Countries, and has worked to promote young researchers to visit Africa and to establish "Emerging Regional Centres of Excellence" there. The [[International Council for Industrial and Applied Mathematics]] gave her their 2019 [[Su Buqing|Su Buchin]] Prize for this work, citing her "long-lasting record actively and efficiently encouraging top-level mathematical research and education in developing African countries".{{r|iciam}}

==Books==
With Bernt Karsten Øksendal and Frank Proske, Di Nunno is a co-author of the book ''Malliavin calculus for Lévy processes with applications to finance'' (Springer, 2009).{{r|malliavin}} She also co-edited ''Advanced Mathematical Methods for Finance'' (Springer, 1011) with Øksendal.

