==Notable achievements==
{{see also|List of International Mathematical Olympiad participants}}
[[File:International Mathematical Olympiad highest team score bar chart.svg|right]]
[[File:International Mathematical Olympiad all-members-gold bar chart.svg|right]]
The following nations have achieved the highest team score in the respective competition:

* [[China]], 19 times (from the first participation in 1985 until 2014): in every year from 1989 to 2014 except 1991, 1994, 1996, 1998, 2003, 2007, 2012;
* [[Soviet Union]], 14 times: in 1963, 1964, 1965, 1966, 1967, 1972, 1973, 1974, 1976, 1979, 1984, 1986, 1988, 1991; 
* [[United States]], 7 times: in 1977, 1981, 1986, 1994, 2015, 2016, 2018;
* [[Hungary]], 6 times: in 1961, 1962, 1969, 1970, 1971, 1975;
* [[Romania]], 5 times: in 1959, 1978, 1985, 1987, 1996;
* [[West Germany]], twice: in 1982 and 1983;
* [[Russia]], twice: in 1999 and 2007;
* [[South Korea]], twice: in 2012 and 2017;
* [[Bulgaria]], once: in 2003;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mmjp.or.jp/jmo/imo2003/contents/results_all.txt|title=Results of the 44th International Mathematical Olympiad|accessdate=2008-03-05}}</ref>
* [[Iran]], once: in 1998;
* [[East Germany]], once: in 1968.

The following nations have achieved an all-members-gold IMO with a full team:

* [[China]], 11 times: in 1992, 1993, 1997, 2000, 2001, 2002, 2004, 2006, 2009, 2010 and 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imo-official.org/country_team_r.aspx?code=CHN|title= Team Results: China at International Mathematical Olympiad}}</ref>
* [[United States]], 3 times: in 1994, 2011, and 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imo-official.org/country_team_r.aspx?code=USA|title= Team Results: US at International Mathematical Olympiad}}</ref>
* [[Russia]], 2 times: in 2002 and 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imo-official.org/country_team_r.aspx?code=RUS|title= Team Results: Russia at International Mathematical Olympiad}}</ref>
* [[South Korea]], twice: in 2012 and 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imo-official.org/country_team_r.aspx?code=KOR|title= Team Results: South Korea at International Mathematical Olympiad}}</ref>
* [[Bulgaria]], once: in 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imo-official.org/country_team_r.aspx?code=BGR|title= Team Results: Bulgaria at International Mathematical Olympiad}}</ref>

The only countries to have their entire team score perfectly in the IMO were the United States in 1994 (they were coached by [[Paul Zeitz]]); and Luxembourg, whose 1-member team had a perfect score in 1981. The US's success earned a mention in ''[[TIME Magazine]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,981185,00.html|title=No. 1 and Counting|accessdate=2010-02-23 | work=Time | date=1994-08-01}}</ref> Hungary won IMO 1975 in an unorthodox way when none of the eight team members received a gold medal (five silver, three bronze). Second place team [[East Germany]] also did not have a single gold medal winner (four silver, four bronze).

Several individuals have consistently scored highly and/or earned medals on the IMO: As of July 2015 Zhuo Qun Song ([[Canada]]) is the most successful participant<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imo-official.org/hall.aspx |title=International Mathematical Olympiad Hall of Fame 2015 |publisher=Imo-official.org |date= |accessdate=2015-07-15}}</ref> with five gold medals (including one perfect score in 2015) and one bronze medal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imo-official.org/participant_r.aspx?id=19624 |title=IMO Official Record for Zhuo Qun (Alex) Song |publisher=Imo-official.org |date= |accessdate=2015-07-15}}</ref> [[Reid W. Barton|Reid Barton]] ([[United States]]) was the first participant to win a gold medal four times (1998-2001).<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.sciencemag.org/cgi/content/summary/293/5530/597|title=IMO's Golden Boy Makes Perfection Look Easy|accessdate=2008-03-05 | doi=10.1126/science.293.5530.597|volume=293|journal=Science|page=597}}</ref> Barton is also one of only eight four-time [[William Lowell Putnam Mathematical Competition#Putnam Fellows|Putnam Fellow]]s (2001–04). [[Christian Reiher]] ([[Germany]]), [[Lisa Sauermann]] ([[Germany]]), [[Teodor von Burg]] ([[Serbia]]), and Nipun Pitimanaaree ([[Thailand]]) are the only other participants to have won four gold medals (2000–03, 2008–11, 2009–12, 2010–13, and 2011–14 respectively); Reiher also received a bronze medal (1999), Sauermann a silver medal (2007), von Burg a silver medal (2008) and a bronze medal (2007), and Pitimanaaree a silver medal (2009).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imo-official.org/hall.aspx|title=International Mathematical Olympiad Hall of Fame|accessdate=2009-07-18}}</ref> [[Wolfgang Burmeister]] ([[East Germany]]), [[Martin Härterich]] ([[West Germany]]), Iurie Boreico ([[Moldova]]), and Lim Jeck ([[Singapore]]) are the only other participants besides Reiher, Sauermann, von Burg, and Pitimanaaree to win five medals with at least three of them gold.<ref name="more">{{cite web|url=https://www.imo-register.org.uk/2017-report.pdf|title=Geoff Smith (August 2017). "UK IMO team leader's report". University of Bath. |accessdate=2018-07-02}}</ref> [[Ciprian Manolescu]] (Romania) managed to write a perfect paper (42 points) for gold medal more times than anybody else in the history of the competition, doing it all three times he participated in the IMO (1995, 1996, 1997).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unl.edu/amc/e-exams/e9-imo/imoteamrecord.shtml|title=IMO team record |accessdate=2008-03-05}}</ref> Manolescu is also a three-time Putnam Fellow (1997, 1998, 2000).<ref name="putnam">{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20000229230334/http://www.maa.org/awards/putnam.html|title=The Mathematical Association of America's William Lowell Putnam Competition|accessdate=2008-03-05}}</ref> [[Eugenia Malinnikova]] ([[Soviet Union]]) is the highest-scoring female contestant in IMO history. She has 3 gold medals in IMO 1989 (41 points), IMO 1990 (42) and IMO 1991 (42), missing only 1 point in 1989 to precede Manolescu's achievement.<ref>{{Harv|Vakil|1997}}</ref>

[[Terence Tao]] (Australia) participated in IMO 1986, 1987 and 1988, winning bronze, silver and gold medals respectively. He won a gold medal when he just turned thirteen in IMO 1988, becoming the youngest person at that time<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iht.com/articles/2007/03/13/news/math.php|title=A packed house for a math lecture? Must be Terence Tao|accessdate=2008-03-05}}</ref> to receive a gold medal (a feat matched in 2011 by Zhuo Qun Song of [[Canada]]). Tao also holds the distinction of being the youngest medalist with his 1986 bronze medal, alongside 2009 bronze medalist [[Raúl Chávez Sarmiento]] (Peru), at the age of 10 and 11 respectively.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.livinginperu.com/news/9641 |title=Peru won four silver and two bronze medals in International Math Olympiad |date=July 22, 2009 |work=Living in Peru }}</ref> Representing the United States, [[Noam Elkies]] won a gold medal with a perfect paper at the age of 14 in 1981. Note that both Elkies and Tao could have participated in the IMO multiple times following their success, but entered university and therefore became ineligible.

The current ten countries with the best all-time results are as follows:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imo-official.org/results_country.aspx?column=awards&order=asc|title=Results: Cumulative Results by Country|publisher=imo-official.org|accessdate=2016-07-20}}</ref>
